Show HN: I'm building megada.sh and the MVP is now free to try with no account
text:
Happy Friday everyone,

Megadash WAS a dashboard tool I built a few months ago to visualise static KPIs. I just wasn't feeling it, nor was anyone else!

So, I have decided to pivot and build something more akin to linktree.

This is still an MVP with no auth - just jump straight in and start creating.

Next on my todo list is to add some basic auth that just asks for an email address, then email you an admin link so you can edit the dashboard in future. Right now, it simply stores a cookie on your device to give you admin access (so dont delete your local storage!).

I will also be adding some basic analytics so you can see how many links have been clicked etc.

Then I will move on to creating a basic landing page, and page a section to feature new dashboards.

I would greatly appreciate any feedback.

Here's one I made earlier...

Making Coffee -> https://www.megada.sh/t--mJLWRBD

Ask HN: From countries outside Twitter Verified places, how’s your experience?
text:
I‘m from Germany and even if I wanted to, Twitter Verified isn‘t available as a subscription here. Only in the US, Canada etc.

It could be entirely placebo, but recently I‘ve seen more verified posts in my timeline and honestly I now feel pretty demotivated from posting. My understanding is that even if no changes were made to the algorithm, Twitter always favored verified accounts.

So since there are now more active verified users, for anyone not within those countries where it is available, I feel like posting isn‘t worth it anymore.

But at the same time, it‘s hard to tell and I‘d rather spend my time on a distribution platform where the mental model is clear.

And before everyone calls me an Elon hater: I think having an 8$ subscription for improving the social graph is actually a neat idea. I just think it‘s currently really half-assed if not everyone can subscribe.

What has your experience been? Do you still get through to your followers? Have you switched to alternatives? Did you get the blue checkmark?

Ask HN: Have you ever used anti detect browsers for web scraping?
text:
I'm in the web scraping industry for a while and I often spend some time creating my "swiss knife" with Playwright or Selenium in case things get tough.
Thanks to a niche substack I'm following, I discovered only today the existence of anti detect browsers like GoLogin and others.
From what I see, they seem a good solution for small projects, but difficult to scale in larger ones for costs of licensing and infrastructure (most of them require a windows machine to run).
Does any of you guys smarter than me use these browsers on a large scale? How is composed your tech stack?

Ask HN: Any well-known FOSS SSO provider with PASETO support?
text:
Ditto. To my understanding, most of the mainstream stuff like Keycloak, Ory Hydra, etc do not support the PASETO standard, which IMO should be preferred over the likes of OIDC, OAuth and the JWT-mess the PASETO tries to supersede.

So, is anyone aware of some project which has built-in PASETO integration?
